One triangle is formed by the points at the vertices of the hexagon, and the other triangle is formed by connecting the points at the midpoints of the sides of the hexagon.

Finally, we consider equilateral triangles with side length \(\sqrt{3}\). These triangles are formed by connecting points that are two units apart along the lattice lines. There are 2 such triangles in the lattice. One triangle is formed by connecting the points at the vertices of the hexagon that are two units apart, and the other triangle is formed by connecting the points at the midpoints of the sides of the hexagon that are two units apart.

Adding up all the equilateral triangles, we get:
\[6 \text{ (side length 1)} + 2 \text{ (side length 2)} + 2 \text{ (side length } \sqrt{3}) = 10\]

Therefore, the number of equilateral triangles with all three vertices in the lattice is \(\boxed{8}\). [asy]size(75);
